Patch Set 3:

Lin, one question based on the resource type associations.  Is there a scheduler filter that uses these or are these more intended to be uses with the filter that matches properties to host aggregate properties?  Also, will these work as scheduler hints?  There is now a UI patch up in horizon to use metadefs in launch instance scheduler hints. I don't know if it will land in Mitaka or not, but if these can be used with scheduler hints the a resource type association of OS::Nova::Server properties target of scheduler_hint would make sense.

And in next patchset, I will change all property name to lowercase. Because it will be converted to lowercase when associated to image, but will not do such thing for others, like host aggregate and flavor. To avoid mismatch of property on different resource, use lowercase by default.

Patch Set 3:

Requesting input form the community. We are inclined to introduce this namespace with a prefix of "cim_" to keep the origin clear and that it is part of a standard. However, Nova filters understand equivalent names such as hw_. Would like to propose in the next release or if the Nova team allows, to modify nova filters to use both names interchangeably where there is commonality. This an "or" style check in the filter code.
Regards

Patch Set 4:

(2 comments)

Two comments inline that I'd like you to address.

@TravisT: would like your opinion on the property names all being lowercase (instead of camel case, as in the CIM docs).  I thought metadefs were case-insensitive?  Or is that only for the purposes of detecting duplicates in the catalog?  Thus consuming services might treat them as case-sensitive.  I'm thinking of this patch that I saw recently: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/275093/

Patch Set 4:

@Brian, technically it will really come down to any code that might actually be using these properties (such as a scheduler filter that is hard coded to them). The Display Name will be used in display purposes.  However, I will say that when you just look at the raw properties when applied to an image, they would be a little easier to read with the original camelcasing, since other "all lower case" properties use and underscore "_" to separate words. Which is all to say, I'd probably lean towards keeping the camel casing.

Patch Set 4:

(2 comments)

Patch Set 4:

Hi Brian and Travis, I totally agree with you that camel case is better choice. But other project, like nova and horizon will issue HEAD request to glance v1/image/<id> to get image data, which will return lowercase property in the header of HTTP response like below shows, even we applied camel case property to image.

X-Image-Meta-Property-Cim_processorarchitecture: x86

This root case is glance will convert it to lowercase when prepare HTTP response header, https://github.com/openstack/glance/blob/master/glance/common/utils.py#L261. And because header name is case-insensitive, eventlet also will format this header name by default, capitalize the first and lowercase others. So user will get a lowercase property name from image. Unfortunately, other project will get origin camel case property name. It will result in mismatch when nova scheduler try to compare them.

So I make a quick solution to change all to lowercase, otherwise it need to make all consuming service to be case-inssensitive. Please let me know if any other solution. Thanks.

Patch Set 6:

For prefix, there is a good suggestion from Deepti. In the patch https://review.openstack.org/#/c/214810/, it will add property as cim_<namespace>_<tag>. E.g, cim_pasd_instructionset for CIM_ProcessorAllocationSettingData's property InstructionSet. It add the CIM class namespace to make CIM class hierarchy to be more clear to both user and other services. So I followed that way to update this patch.

I'd really prefer to see the CamelCase property names, but I understand your point.  I circulated a message about this on the dev list, let's see if anyone has any strong feelings.

I think we should use CamelCase and document better in Glance that consumers should normalize property names before doing comparisons.

We already have this problem now because you can create CamelCased property names using the Images v2 API, but they are returned to you as all lowercase if you use the glanceclient in v1 mode or use the novaclient or Compute v2 API.  So people already should be treating image property names as case-insensitive.

Patch Set 6:

Patch Set 6:

OK, so the situation here is even more complicated than I thought.

If you look at the Images v1 API and Compute v2 API responses at the bottom of this etherpad:

https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/images-v1-v2-property-names-asymmetry

you can see that there are some Images v1 responses that respect camel case, even though some do not.

I'm inclined to think that for the purposes of this particular spec, we should go ahead and use the CamelCased property names to enhance readability.  Consumers of the property names just need to be aware that they should be treated as case-insensitive.
